Jacqueline Zamitalo is a second-year Computer Science major and International Engineering minor in the Burnett Honors College at the University of Central Florida. She loves programming and welcomes every chance to practice and learn the concepts, languages, and skills behind software engineering.

While at UCF, Jacqueline has served as an Undergraduate Teaching Assistant in Concepts in Computer Science and Computer Science 1, two of the foundational CS courses at UCF. In these roles, she's used her knowledge of Python and C to assist students in their CS journeys. Additionally, she's spent a semester interning at a local non-profit, where she worked on the Computer Programming team, and she has joined multiple student organizations, including the Society of Women Engineers, KnightHacks, and the Google Student Developer Club. In the upcoming semester, she will also be serving as a Teacher's Assistant for UCF's introductory Python course. Outside of school, Jacqueline enjoys reading, writing, watching movies, playing sports, and learning languages.

Jacqueline's passion for technology and learning is what led her to join the Wall-E project. As Programming Lead, Jacqueline will be fulfilling the software requirements for the project, which involves programming the robot's Arduinos and designing and building this website. She looks forward to demonstrating how collaboration between various engineering fields can make something as incredible as a life-sized Wall-E.
